West 151st Street, west from Seventh, to and including Eighth Aves. Note station of the Ninth Ave., Elevated on Eighth Ave.

August 29, 1935.

P. L. Sperr.

(1) The new United States Government Housing development on Seventh Ave. (right) north from West 151st (Foreground) to 153rd Streets, and west to Macombs Place (left). North of this development and south of the Central Bridge (West 155th Street), appears Harlem Lane Park; a small triangular plot at the convergence of Seventh Ave., and Macombs Place at West 155th Street.

September 19, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

(2) A more extensive view northward. Note the serpentine course of the Harlem River. Crossing same, in the order of their appearance, are the Central (West 155th Street) Bridge, the New York and Putman R.R. Bridge (about West 158th Street) and High Bridge (about West 174th Street).

September 19, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

(3) A view north west and showing prominently the Macombs Place side. Shown on the extreme left, are buildings at the N.W. corner of West 152nd Street.

September 19, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

(1)
Seventh Ave., north from about West 151st Street, to the Central Bridge (155th Street), which crosses the Harlem River to the Borough of Bronx. Shown on both sides of Seventh Ave., is work in progress for a U.S. Government slum clearance and low cost housing development, under the auspices of the W.P.A. and P.W.A.

September 19, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
Another view slightly northward.

Seventh Ave. (foreground), east side, south from West 152nd to West 151st Streets, showing car yards of the Interborough Rapid Transit Co. Also shown is a general view in a southeasterly direction with the Harlem River and the western shore of the Bronx across it, appearing on the left. Note also the Central Bridge across the Harlem River.
September 19, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.
